<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-271-061  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 271 061.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 23 1989 v23 n3 p29(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>DEC's desktop helps automate radiology labs.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Cortese, Amy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>DEC workstations and software introduced in Jan 1989 work togetherto create an integrated text and medical imaging system, DECofficials claim.andP;  An example of such a system would be a radiologyimage displayed in one workstation window while information frompatient records is displayed in another.andP;  The necessary pieces forsuch a system are Decwindows software, Vax-image ApplicationServices software tools and the new desktop workstations inconjunction with Decrad, DEC's radiology software.andP;  Decwindowswill be included in Release 5.1 of VMS, expected in Feb 1989.andP;  Theproducts will reportedly be integrated with other DEC and non-DECproducts.andP;  Data formatting technology developed by DEC and SiemensMedical Systems Inc makes it possible for the workstations to takeover some work of radiology-specific hardware.andP;  Vaxstation models3100, 3520 and 3540 will be most cost effective in thisapplication, DEC officials say.andP;  DEC estimates a sophisticatedradiology department could be automated for $500,000andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Product:   DEC VAXstation 3100 (Workstation) (usage)DEC VAXstation 3520 (Workstation) (usage)DEC VAXstation 3540 (Workstation) (usage)Decrad (Computer graphics software) (usage).andO;Topic:     RadiologyApplicationsMedical RecordsWorkstationsGraphics Software.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>